{
  "answer": "All three texts are present in the corpus and offer distinct but related perspectives on kingship.\n\n**Manu Chapter 7** (work_slug: unknown-manusmrti-347b76, chapter 7): Manu opens with the king's divine composition — he is formed from extracted particles of eight gods: Indra, Wind, Yama, the Sun, Agni, Varuna, the Moon, and Kubera (Mn_7.4–5). This cosmic origin means the king surpasses all beings in splendor and must not be despised even as a child (Mn_7.5–8). The central qualifying concept is mastery of Daṇḍa (the rod of punishment), which Manu treats as Dharma itself (Mn_7.18). To wield it rightly, the king must be truthful, deliberate, wise, knowing of the three goals (dharma, wealth, desire), pure, true to his word, follow the sacred treatises, and have good assistants (Mn_7.26, 31). He must conquer his senses and avoid eighteen vices — ten born of desire (hunting, gambling, sleeping by day, slander, women, intoxication, song/dance/music, and aimless wandering) and eight born of anger (malice, violence, treachery, envy, calumny, misappropriation of property, and harshness of speech and punishment) (Mn_7.44–48). Manu's king is primarily a righteous wielder of punishment who protects all varnas and āśramas (Mn_7.35) — the theology of kingship dominates, while procedural court mechanics are absent.\n\n**Viṣṇu Smṛti Chapter 3** (work_slug: unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8, chapter 3): Viṣṇu opens concisely — 'Now, the duties of a king (rājadharma)' — and moves immediately to practical administration rather than divine-origin theology. The king must protect the people (Vi_3.2) and uphold the varṇa/āśrama system (Vi_3.3). He manages a hierarchical administrative structure: village chiefs, superintendents of ten, a hundred, and a whole district (Vi_3.7–14), each redressing wrongs at their level. He appoints specialist officials by quality — pious men for pious duties, skilled for finance, brave for military, fierce for fierce deeds (Vi_3.17–20). Diplomatically, he uses conciliation, dissension, bribery, and force as appropriate (Vi_3.38). For legal disputes, Viṣṇu specifies that the king should personally examine cases with learned Brahmins, or alternatively appoint a Brahmin to examine them (Vi_3.72–73). Court assessors must be of good birth, impartial toward friend and foe, and uncorrupted by lust, anger, fear, or greed (Vi_3.74). Viṣṇu echoes Manu's daṇḍa language (Vi_3.95 ~ Mn_7.25) but adds a more humane note: 'The king who is happy in his subjects' happiness, and who is unhappy in their sorrow … is glorified in heaven after death' (Vi_3.98). Compared to Manu, Viṣṇu is more administrative and less theological, giving brief but direct guidelines on the king's participation in legal adjudication.\n\n**Bṛhaspati Smṛti** (work_slug: unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070, chapter 1 — titled 'The Section on Legal Procedure'): Bṛhaspati shares the divine-origin narrative (from Soma, Agni, Sun, Wind, Indra, Lord of Wealth, Lord of Waters, and Yama — Brh_1,1.6–7) but pivots immediately to the institutional mechanics of legal procedure. He systematizes the king's role far beyond the other two:\n\n1. *Jurisdiction and topics*: Legal disputes are of two kinds — arising from wealth (fourteen sub-types including lending, deposits, boundary disputes, theft, partition) and violence (four sub-types: two kinds of assault, homicide, adultery) (Brh_1,1.9–16).\n\n2. *Four means of decision*: dharma, legal procedure, custom, and the king's edict — the last being the highest override, superseding custom (Brh_1,1.18–21). This formally positions the king as the apex authority in law.\n\n3. *Court conduct*: The king, together with his ministers and family priest, must examine legal disputes according to the treatise on dharma, 'free from anger and greed, truthful and self-controlled' (Brh_1,1.22).\n\n4. *Ten-limbed court structure*: The court is compared to a sacrifice (Brh_1,1.83). The king is the head; the prāḍvivāka (the chief judicial officer who asks questions and cross-examines) is the mouth; the assessors are the arms; the Smṛti the hands; the accountant and scribe the shanks (Brh_1,1.84–88). The king is 'the speaker and chief, the ruler; the assessor is the examiner of the case' (Brh_1,1.88).\n\n5. *Four court types*: stationary (town/village), non-stationary (mobile), sealed (with a presiding officer), and directed — 'one attended by the king' (Brh_1,1.57–58). The king's personal presence defines the highest court.\n\n6. *Delegation and accountability*: 'The legal procedure, though one, has been declared to be manifold by the wise; the decider of it is the king, or a Brahmin of great learning' (Brh_1,1.67). The king accompanied by the prāḍvivāka, ministers, priest, and assessors 'acts as an observer according to dharma' (Brh_1,1.70). He must protect both plaintiff and defendant (Brh_1,1.60) and must not punish the unpunishable or fail to punish the punishable (Brh_1,1.77).\n\n**Synthesis — three voices**: Manu establishes the metaphysical ground (divine origin) and the moral-qualitative requirements for kingship, centering on the proper wielding of Daṇḍa. Viṣṇu translates this into administrative and governance duties, adding brief but clear directives about the king's personal role in adjudicating disputes with Brahmin assistance. Bṛhaspati elaborates legal procedure into a formal institutional system where the king sits at the apex as head of a ten-limbed court, surrounded by the prāḍvivāka, assessors, scribe, and accountant — transforming the king from sole wielder of punishment into the presiding head of a differentiated judicial apparatus. The progression is from theology (Manu) → governance (Viṣṇu) → procedural jurisprudence (Bṛhaspati).",
